\title{Paperproof Validator}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Formal Proof Visualization and Verification for Lean 4"}

\subtree{
\title{paperproof-validator}
\blockquote{Formal Proof Visualization and Verification for Lean 4}

\p{\strong{Version}: 1.0.0 \strong{Trit}: -1 (Validator - verifies proof correctness) \strong{Bundle}: verification \strong{Status}: ✅ New (Lean 4 theorem proof visualization) \strong{Repository}: [Paper-Proof/paperproof](https://github.com/Paper-Proof/paperproof)}

\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{\strong{Paperproof Validator} transforms formal Lean 4 proofs into intuitive, paper-like visualizations. It bridges the gap between abstract formal proofs and human understanding by displaying how hypotheses and goals evolve throughout a proof.}

\p{\strong{Key Innovation}: Makes formal proofs accessible by visualizing proof structure in a way that mirrors mathematical notation on paper.}

\subtree{
\title{What Paperproof Does}
\p{Instead of abstract Lean code:}

\pre{\startverb
theorem example : P → Q := by
  intro h
  apply some_lemma
  exact h.right
\stopverb}

\p{Paperproof shows:}

\pre{\startverb
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Hypotheses (green nodes):           │
│  - h : P                            │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Goal (red node):                    │
│  - Q                                │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Tactics (transparent):              │
│  - apply some_lemma                 │
│  - exact h.right                    │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Architecture}
\subtree{
\title{Three Core Components}
\subtree{
\title{1. \strong{Lean 4 Library Integration}}
\pre{\startverb
import Paperproof

theorem my_theorem : P ∧ Q → R := by
  -- Paperproof automatically extracts proof state
  intro ⟨hp, hq⟩
  -- Visualization tracks hypotheses and goals
  exact some_proof_term
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Capabilities}:}

\ul{
\li{Integrates with Lean 4 InfoTree}
\li{Extracts proof state at each tactic}
\li{Provides proof metadata to VS Code extension}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. \strong{VS Code Extension}}
\p{\strong{Responsibilities}:}

\ul{
\li{Tracks cursor position (detects which theorem is being visualized)}
\li{Communicates with Lean server for proof data}
\li{Hosts webview panel for visualization}
\li{Provides commands and settings}
\li{Bridges Lean InfoTree to React frontend}
}

\p{\strong{Commands}:}

\pre{\startverb
Paperproof: Open Paperproof Panel
Paperproof: Show Current Theorem
Paperproof: Export Proof as Image
Paperproof: Settings
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Architecture Flow}:}

\pre{\startverb
User Cursor on Theorem
           ↓
Selection Changed Event
           ↓
Request Proof Data from Lean Server
           ↓
Lean Server Returns InfoTree
           ↓
BetterParser (extract structure)
           ↓
Converter Service (optimize for visualization)
           ↓
Send to React Frontend
           ↓
Render Visual Proof Tree
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. \strong{React Frontend Visualization}}
\p{\strong{Component Hierarchy}:}

\pre{\startverb
ProofTree (root)
├── GlobalContext Provider
├── Header (title, controls)
└── BoxEl (variable scope container)
    ├── Hypotheses Section
    │   └── HypothesisNode (green)
    │       └── Transparency = "in scope"
    ├── Tactics Section
    │   └── TacticNode (transparent, dashed border)
    │       └── Arrows to related nodes
    └── Goals Section
        └── GoalNode (red)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Visual Cues}:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Hypotheses}: Green nodes at the top}
\li{\strong{Goals}: Red nodes at the bottom}
\li{\strong{Tactics}: Transparent nodes with dashed borders}
\li{\strong{Scope}: Nested boxes with darkening backgrounds}
\li{\strong{Availability}: Node opacity indicates scope accessibility}
}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Capabilities}
\subtree{
\title{1. visualize-proof-structure}
\p{Display proof as hierarchical tree with visual nodes:}

\pre{\startverb
from paperproof_validator import PaperproofVisualizer

visualizer = PaperproofVisualizer(
    lean_file="example.lean",
    theorem_name="my_theorem"
)

# Extract and render proof
proof_visual = visualizer.visualize(
    show_hypotheses=True,
    show_goals=True,
    show_tactics=True,
    show_scopes=True
)

# Output: Interactive HTML/React visualization
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. extract-proof-metadata}
\p{Pull structured proof information from Lean InfoTree:}

\pre{\startverb
-- Lean 4 code
theorem and_comm (p q : Prop) : p ∧ q → q ∧ p := by
  intro ⟨hp, hq⟩      -- Step 1: intro creates hypotheses
  exact ⟨hq, hp⟩      -- Step 2: exact provides proof term
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Extracted Structure}:}

\pre{\startverb
{
  "theorem": "and_comm",
  "steps": [
    {
      "tactic": "intro",
      "hypotheses": [
        {"name": "hp", "type": "p"},
        {"name": "hq", "type": "q"}
      ],
      "goals": [{"type": "q ∧ p"}]
    },
    {
      "tactic": "exact",
      "hypotheses": [
        {"name": "hp", "type": "p"},
        {"name": "hq", "type": "q"}
      ],
      "goals": []
    }
  ]
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. validate-proof-correctness}
\p{Verify that proof reaches expected conclusion:}

\pre{\startverb
validation = visualizer.validate_proof(
    expected_conclusion="Q"
)

if validation.passes:
    print("✓ Proof correctly establishes Q")
else:
    print(f"✗ Proof does not establish Q")
    print(f"  Final goal: {validation.final_goal}")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. analyze-tactic-effects}
\p{Show how each tactic transforms proof state:}

\pre{\startverb
analysis = visualizer.analyze_tactics()

for step in analysis.steps:
    print(f"\nTactic: {step.name}")
    print(f"Hypotheses before: {step.hypotheses_before}")
    print(f"Hypotheses after: {step.hypotheses_after}")
    print(f"Goals before: {step.goals_before}")
    print(f"Goals after: {step.goals_after}")
    print(f"Variables in scope: {step.scope}")
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. support-multiple-proof-tactics}
\p{Handle common Lean 4 tactics:}

\pre{\startverb
-- apply: Uses a hypothesis/lemma to transform goal
theorem proof_with_apply : P → Q := by
  intro hp
  apply lemma_p_implies_q
  exact hp

-- have: Introduces intermediate hypothesis
theorem proof_with_have : P → Q → R := by
  intro hp hq
  have h : X := lemma_from_p hp
  apply lemma_h_q_to_r h hq

-- induction: Proves by induction
theorem induction_proof : ∀ n, P n := by
  intro n
  induction n with
  | zero => exact base_case
  | succ k ih => exact inductive_step k ih

-- by_contra: Proof by contradiction
theorem by_contra_proof : P := by
  by_contra hnp
  have : False := contradiction_from_not_p hnp
  exact absurd this (by simp)

-- cases: Case analysis
theorem cases_proof : P := by
  cases some_disjunction with
  | left h => exact left_proof h
  | right h => exact right_proof h
\stopverb}

\p{All tactics are visualized with their proof state transformations.}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. export-proof-visualization}
\p{Generate static or interactive proof representations:}

\pre{\startverb
# Export as interactive HTML
visualizer.export_html("proof.html")

# Export as static image (PNG/SVG)
visualizer.export_image("proof.png", format="png")

# Export as LaTeX (for papers)
visualizer.export_latex("proof.tex")

# Export as JSON (for programmatic use)
visualizer.export_json("proof.json")
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Integration with Lean 4 Ecosystem}
\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\pre{\startverb
# 1. Install VS Code Extension
# Via VS Code Extensions marketplace: search "Paperproof"

# 2. Add to Lean project (lakefile.toml)
require paperproof from git
  "https://github.com/Paper-Proof/paperproof.git"

# 3. Update
lake update

# 4. Import in Lean files
import Paperproof
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Usage in Lean 4}
\pre{\startverb
import Paperproof

-- Define a theorem
theorem associativity : ∀ (a b c : Nat), (a + b) + c = a + (b + c) := by
  intro a b c
  -- When cursor is here, Paperproof shows:
  -- - Hypotheses: a : Nat, b : Nat, c : Nat
  -- - Goal: (a + b) + c = a + (b + c)
  induction a with
  | zero =>
    -- Paperproof shows base case context
    rfl
  | succ k ih =>
    -- Paperproof shows inductive step
    -- - ih : (k + b) + c = k + (b + c) [inductive hypothesis]
    simp [Nat.add_succ, ih]
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Formal Proof Theory Background}
\subtree{
\title{Proof Trees and Natural Deduction}
\p{Paperproof visualization is based on natural deduction systems:}

\pre{\startverb
Hypotheses (context)
───────────────────────
    | Tactics apply
    | Goal transforms
───────────────────────
    Final conclusion
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Gentzen Sequent Calculus Connection}
\p{Paperproof extends traditional proof visualization with modern web technologies:}

\p{\strong{Traditional Gentzen style}:}

\pre{\startverb
Γ ⊢ A    Γ ⊢ B
──────────────────
  Γ ⊢ A ∧ B
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Paperproof visualization}:}

\ul{
\li{Shows Γ (hypotheses) visually}
\li{Shows goals in red}
\li{Shows proof steps with connecting arrows}
\li{Indicates variable scope with nested boxes}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Color Semantics}
\pre{\startverb
| Color | Element | Meaning |
|-------|---------|---------|
| Green | Hypotheses | Available facts in scope |
| Red | Goals | Targets to prove |
| Transparent | Tactics | Proof steps (white box) |
| Dark gray | Scope boundaries | Variable scope nesting |
| Opacity | Node visibility | Whether element is in scope |
\stopverb}
}
}

